---
title: Ronin - Toolkit for building shining CLI programs with Node.js
---

<header class="text-center">
  <%= image_tag '/images/logo@3x.jpg', class: 'logo block-center img-responsive' %>
  <h1>Ronin</h1>
  <h4>Toolkit for building shining CLI programs with Node.js</h4>
  <h4>Automatically builds commands based on project structure</h4>
  <% code('javascript') do %>
  // commands/apps/add.js
  var AddApplication = Command.extend({
    desc: 'Create new application',
    options: {
      verbose: 'boolean'
    },
    
    run: function (verbose, name) {
      // verbose = true, name = "hello-world"
    }
  });
  
  $ my-program apps add --verbose hello-world
  <% end %>
</header>

<nav>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="https://github.com/vdemedes/ronin" target="_blank">Github</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <%= link_to 'Quick Start', '/guides/getting-started' %>
    </li>
    <li>
      <%= link_to 'Guides', '/guides' %>
    </li>
  </ul>
</nav>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-center">Features</h2>
	
	<div class="container u-full-width features">
		<div class="row">
			<div class="five columns">
				<h4>Commands based on project structure <span class="badge">wow</span></h4>
				<p>
					Ronin is building commands based on how you structure your project.
					Create <i>add.js</i> inside <i>apps</i> folder and <mark>apps add</mark> command is there.
				</p>
			</div>
			
			<div class="five columns">
				<h4>Forced code organization</h4>
				<p>
					Because Ronin depends on your project structure, it automatically forces you to structure your code in a comfortable way.
					Each namespace has its folder and all commands that belong to it are in that folder.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		
		<div class="row">
			<div class="five columns">
				<h4>Middleware</h4>
				<p>
					Avoid repeating yourself and specify middleware for each command.
					Useful for authentication, validation, etc.
				</p>
			</div>
			
			<div class="five columns">
				<h4>Auto-generated help</h4>
				<p>
					Ronin generates help for a whole program, individual namespace or command.
					There is also ability to customize help output.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		
		<div class="row">
			<div class="five columns">
				<h4>Local and global options</h4>
				<p>
					You can easily specify command and global options, their types, aliases and default values.
					Their values is passed to command as function arguments in the order they were defined.
				</p>
			</div>
			
			<div class="five columns">
				<h4>One command to get started</h4>
				<p>
					Ronin ships with a Yeoman generator, that will get you started in less than a minute.
					It creates a base for your CLI program, installs dependencies and links it, so that it's accessible from $PATH.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
		
		<div class="row">
		  <div class="five columns">
		    <h4>Small codebase and test coverage</h4>
		    <p>
		      Ronin's codebase is only 269 sloc.
		      Every piece of Ronin is carefully tested.
		  </div>
		  
		  <div class="five columns">
		    <p class="coming-soon">
		      More features coming soon.
		      Open a <a href="https://github.com/vdemedes/ronin/issues" target="_blank">github issue</a> if you have suggestions.
		    </p>
		  </div>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>

<section>
  <h2 class="text-center">Try it out!</h2>
  <p>
    Ronin will help you focus on building your CLI application, rather than on <b>how</b> to build a CLI application.
    To get you started, there is a <%= link_to 'Getting Started', '/guides/getting-started' %> tutorial, where you will create your first CLI program with Ronin.
    There are also <b>non-boring</b> <%= link_to 'guides', '/guides' %> available, if you want to know more.
